{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585236"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:06:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:06:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14938"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14938","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14938"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.27,0.28,0.12,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7626"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74786"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7626","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7626"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14938"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60272"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"11192"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18648"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23995"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24082"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74786","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74786"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher is studying the transmission of tularaemia, a zoonotic bacterial infection caused by \u003Cem\u003EFrancisella tularensis\u003C/em\u003E that primarily affects animals but can also infect humans. The disease can be transmitted through multiple routes including arthropod bites, direct contact with infected animals, or inhalation of contaminated aerosols.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a reservoir host for tularaemia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Deer fly","Brown rat","Rabbits","Wood tick","House mouse"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETularaemia is a zoonotic disease caused by the bacterium \u003Cem\u003EFrancisella tularensis\u003C/em\u003E. The \u003Cstrong\u003EEuropean rabbit\u003C/strong\u003E is one of the most important reservoir hosts for this pathogen, along with other lagomorphs like hares. These animals maintain the bacteria in nature and can transmit it to humans through various routes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ebrown rat\u003C/strong\u003E, while susceptible to tularaemia infection, is not considered a significant reservoir host for the disease. They may occasionally become infected but do not play a major role in maintaining the pathogen in nature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ehouse mouse\u003C/strong\u003E, similar to rats, can become infected with \u003Cem\u003EF. tularensis\u003C/em\u003E but is not considered an important reservoir host for maintaining the disease cycle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edeer fly\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ewood tick\u003C/strong\u003E are vectors that can transmit tularaemia between animals and to humans, but they are not reservoir hosts. These arthropods become temporarily infected after feeding on infected animals but do not maintain the bacteria long-term in nature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the distinction between reservoir hosts and vectors is crucial for disease control. While arthropods are the primary mode of transmission to humans, it is the reservoir hosts like rabbits that maintain the pathogen in the environment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Rabbits and hares are important reservoir hosts for Francisella tularensis.","Multiple mammalian species can serve as reservoir hosts for tularaemia.","Ticks and deer flies are important vectors but not reservoir hosts for tularaemia."],"references":["Plymoth M, Lundqvist R, Nystedt A, Sj\u00f6stedt A, Gustafsson TN. Targeting Tularemia: Clinical, Laboratory, and Treatment Outcomes From an 11-year Retrospective Observational Cohort in Northern Sweden [published correction appears in Clin Infect Dis. 2024 Jul 19;79(1):284. doi: 10.1093/cid/ciae175]. Clin Infect Dis. 2024;78(5):1222-1231. doi:10.1093/cid/ciae098"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60272"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14938"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60272"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-27T06:56:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-27T06:57:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7626"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74786"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4944","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4944"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Microbiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T15:37:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"14"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11192"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Tularemia","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-12-27T06:54:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-27T06:54:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"contributions","id":"18648","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/contributions/18648"},"attributes":{"finalizedAt":"2024-11-07T20:36:13+10:30","userDetails":{"name":"Jun Yen Ng","title":"Dr","isExpert":true,"position":"Haematology Advanced Trainee","training":"Registrar","credentials":"BMedSci (Hons), MBBS, MClinTRes"